th small features or wall thicknesses you want to make sure that you are conforming to whatever material properties you are working with. <a href=\"http://www.shapeways.com/materials/material-options\" title=\"Material Options\">Material Options</a>\r\n\r\n<h2>Upload Your Model</h2>\r\nOnce you have your model prepped and ready for upload, you can upload it in several ways. For models that are not going to be printed in full color, you\'ll be uploading a STL file. This can be done manually by doing a save-as STL and uploading the file to Shapeways, or you can use the <a href=\"http://www.shapeways.com/tutorials/solid_works_add-in\" title=\"ShapeWays Add-In\">Shapeways Add-In</a> for SolidWorks. \r\n\r\n','Prepping and Uploading a model with SolidWorks','','inherit','open','open','','662-revision-4','','','2012-07-25 11:27:41','2012-07-25 18:27:41','',662,'http://swztest.solidwize.com/2012/07/25/662-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(667,2,'2012-07-25 13:38:21','2012-07-25 20:38:21','<h2>Create Your Model</h2>\r\n\r\nIf you\'re new to SolidWorks, check out the video below on creating a simple bone wrench. \r\n\r\nIf you\'ve been using SolidWorks for any length of time, you probably no what you want to create and how you\'re going to go about modelling it. Keep in mind that when you export the file, all solid bodies will be translated, and all surface bodies will be ignored. When working with parts with small features or wall thicknesses you want to make sure that you are conforming to whatever material properties you are working with. <a href=\"http://www.shapeways.com/materials/material-options\" title=\"Material Options\">Material Options</a>\r\n\r\n<h2>Upload Your Model</h2>\r\nOnce you have your model prepped and ready for upload, you can upload it in several ways. For models that are not going to be printed in full color, you\'ll be uploading a STL file. This can be done manually by doing a save-as STL and uploading the file to Shapeways, or you can use the <a hre