s_add-in\" title=\"ShapeWays Add-In\">Shapeways Add-In</a> for SolidWorks. With either of these options, you need to set the quality first before saving the file out. \r\n\r\nFor full color parts, you\'ll need to save the file out as a VRML file and then upload directly to Shapeways. In the save-as options for VRML, the output format needs to be set to VRML 97 or the upload will fail. Check out the video below for a full explanation for both file types\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/46383998\" width=\"1000\" height=\"594\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>','Prepping and Uploading a model with SolidWorks','','inherit','open','open','','662-revision-6','','','2012-07-25 13:39:00','2012-07-25 20:39:00','',662,'http://swztest.solidwize.com/2012/07/25/662-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(669,2,'2012-07-25 13:45:47','2012-07-25 20:45:47','<h2>Create Your Model</h2>\n\nIf you\'re new to SolidWorks, check out the video below on creating a simple bone wrench. \n\nOnce you complete your model, you\'ll want to keep in mind that when you export the file, that only Solid Bodies will be exported for STL files and whatever is visible will be uploaded for a VRML file (full color) When working with parts with small features or wall thicknesses you want to make sure that you adhere to the limitations of the material that you want to print in. The <a href=\"http://www.shapeways.com/materials/material-options\" title=\"Material Options\">Material Options</a> gives you guidelines for the parameters that you\'ll need to meet for each materal.\n\n<h2>Upload Your Model</h2>\nOnce you have your model prepped and ready for upload, you can upload it in several ways. For models that are not going to be printed in full color, you\'ll be uploading a STL file. This can be done manually by doing a save-as STL and uploading the file to Shapeways, or you can use the <a href=\"http://www.shapeways.com/tutorials/solid_work